<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS FOR COOK</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 24 19:57:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
I agree with Chet on his view of Doc Spatz. Doc Spatz is comming in from a very different angle, and he is honest. One fault he does have is that he gets cranky once in a while (Doc, are you reading this?), as we see from his recent twitches on poetry and literary works on this site.<br><br>
Actually, Doc Spatz is not a communist sympathizer. He is far from it. He sits in that group of people who had legitimate problems with the Vietnam War, and he chose to deal with the War in ways that were different from many of the rest of us. It took me quite a while to begin to see and feel his point of view, and he mine. I must acknowledge that my pride in this country, my duty, and belief in the Constitution and Bill of Rghts, was a base for my participation in the Vietnam War and the preservation of our way of life. I did fight, so to speak, to preserve the right of the Spatz's of this country to disagree. He did serve the country as a CO. <br><br>
There are people I have met here on this site who are conscientious objectors, whose life view holds combat unacceptable. I have nothing but the greatest respect for those individuals. Doc Spatz's view, though not of a religious wellspring, was carefully thought out, philosophical, and also worthy of respect.<br><br>
I have managed to separate out those individuals for whom I have the greatest contempt, the Jane Fondas and the cretin crowd who shouted epithets, spat, and called me a baby killer. I has not been easy, and I still have a way to go in dealing with this subject. The blood still runs hot.<br><br>
Cook, take Chet's coments as constructive. This is a very diverse group here, and we should strive for equilibrium of sorts if we are all to be winners.<br><br>
Arthur<br><br>

